The customer, Jennifer Palmer, claims the store manager acted very badly. She says he was told about the spill twice but did nothing about it because he was eating dinner.

A judge is unlikely to throw out Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To get this kind of damages, the customer must show that the store manager acted on purpose and with a complete disregard for the harm that could happen. Jennifer Palmer can say that the store manager should have known about the danger because many other customers had slipped and fallen on the same issue in the past. The manager still did nothing. Jennifer Palmer can also say that the manager's behavior was very bad because he ignored the problem even though it had happened many times before.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee of the store told the manager about the spill. The manager said he was busy eating and did not have time to help. Fifteen minutes later, another employee told the manager about the spill, and he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell and got hurt. Before that, five other customers had slipped and fallen in the same store in 2009.

Jennifer Palmer is suing the store for money to pay for her injury and for extra money as punishment. We are thinking about asking the judge to throw out the part of the lawsuit that asks for punitive damages.

In California, a person can get punitive damages if someone breaks a rule that is not part of a contract. The rule says that someone can get punitive damages if the person acted with evil or was very mean and showed a complete disregard for the safety of others. The court has said that someone acts with malice when they are aware of the danger and do nothing to stop it.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. A big question in class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is even more important today. Looking back on events since 9/11, I have seen how the media view Islam changed. In 2001, it was mostly negative. Today, it is very accepting of Islam in America. Now we have a president named Barack Obama, whose family has Muslim background.

The story of the Prophet is interesting to me. It says Muhammad was a kind and humble man. This is different from what I thought I knew about him. I thought he made people join Islam by force. He would conquer cities and make people follow Islam. But the story says Muhammad was a hero who was misunderstood. People saw the good in him and wanted to learn from him.

There are some similarities between the teachings of Jesus and the actions of Muhammad. One example is when he made food multiply to feed many people. This makes me think the writers wanted us to see Muhammad as a great teacher who didn't need to prove himself. They wanted us to see that he was a man of truth and miracles. This is dishonest because it takes away from the special story of Jesus Christ. It's like they are taking credit for Jesus' work.

Some stories in the biography seem to be about proving that many people converted to Islam on their own. But these stories are not direct. They tell us what someone else heard from someone else. This makes the stories seem less true. I don't like this because it makes the story seem suspicious.

What bothers me most is that the biography makes Muhammad seem like a perfect man. It says he was kind and gentle. But history says he was not. I wonder if Muslims know the true story of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus were not followed by his followers after he died.  A movement of Christian thought happened after his death.  This movement moved away from Jesus' ideas.  If we look at this history, we see that Christianity has changed a lot over time.  It has moved away from its start.  Today, people are starting to think differently.  Many people are aware of this change and want to know more.  Some people still believe in the old teachings.  They will not change their minds.  But they may not be able to stop the change.  Many Christians will learn more about the past.  This will make them want to go back to the original ideas of Jesus.  This will take a long time, maybe even centuries.  But it will happen.  There will be a time when Christians go back to the original teachings of Jesus.  A movement will grow and people will remove the extra teachings that were added over time.  This will make Christianity like it was when Jesus lived.  When this happens in the United States and Europe, many people will follow Jesus' ideas.  The church will remain strong to lead the way.  But the church will not be the same.  People will think and believe the same way.  There will be less difference between different groups of Christians.  This has happened before.  A long time ago, Christians were persecuted.  Then they became the rulers.  Our country used to treat African-Americans unfairly.  Now they have leaders.  The same thing will happen with Christianity.  People will go back to the start and forget the extra teachings.

If we look back in time, we see that there was only one kind of Jewish religion.  But over time, the Jewish people divided into groups.  These groups were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and many ordinary people.  They did not agree with each other.  They had different ideas about God.

The Jungle shows how people are naturally selfish. They want to make their lives better, but they do not care about others. The main factory owners and managers are very greedy. They want to make their businesses big and strong, but they do not think about people or animals who might be hurt. They do not care about the pollution from their factories or the dirty water and air.

The factory owners do not care about their workers. They want to make more money, so they make their workers work very long hours. They can lay off many workers at any time without giving them anything. There were no laws to protect workers in those days. The factory owners could do what they wanted. They made their workers work in bad conditions. People who worked in the factories were treated very badly. They were living in very poor conditions and had no help. Unions were formed to help workers, but they often made money from the workers instead of helping them. Workers had no way to get out of this bad situation. They were like slaves. Many workers were poor and hungry, and they had to ask for help from the factory owners. This made immorality common.

This book, The Jungle, shows how people are treated unfairly. It shows how some people are very cruel and only care about themselves. The author, Upton Sinclair, wants to show us the problems that exist in the world.

Some authors use different ways to make readers feel a certain way about important subjects. They use many techniques. Some are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. He uses a special way of combining words to give readers a certain feeling. Sometimes, he pairs an adjective and a noun that do not usually go together. This creates a special meaning around a subject. 

Fitzgerald uses this technique with colors. He gives meaning to many colors, including gold, green, white, gray, and red. In The Great Gatsby, he creates meaning for white and gray. White is nice and high class. Gray is old and faded. Fitzgerald starts to use these meanings in the beginning of the novel. 

In the beginning, everyone wears white. The rich characters, like Daisy and Jordan, wear white. Nick wears white flannel to Gatsby's party. Tom wears a white shirt. Even houses are white. The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting an impression of Gatsby's party. But even then, the colors are bright and not white. 

Fitzgerald uses the colors to describe many everyday things. He makes some people and places seem unimportant by using the colors white and gray. He describes Jordan and Daisy's childhood as a "white girlhood". He says there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes. He describes an old man as gray. 

After creating these meanings, Fitzgerald uses the colors to show that some subjects are unimportant. He uses the colors to describe Daisy. He says she is dressed in white in a white car. Fitzgerald uses this technique again and again to show that Daisy is just a uniform addition. He says Daisy's fur collar is gray and she wears a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's meeting. 

Fitzgerald uses colors in a special way to give readers a certain feeling about important objects and people. He creates meaning for colors and then uses that meaning to remind readers of a feeling.

San Diego County is a great place for growing food. The weather is nice and sunny. Many crops grow well there, like tomatoes, citrus fruits, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers.

There is a big market for organic food in the San Diego area. Many people want to buy food from local farms. Some farms in the area offer tours and allow people to walk around and enjoy nature.

Organic farming helps the environment. It makes the area better for plants and animals. But it can be more difficult and costly than other ways of farming. Organic farmers need to work harder to keep pests and weeds away and make the soil healthy. They also need to spend more time and money.

The land in question is in a good place for this kind of farming. It is near a town called Potrero in San Diego County. The land is 160 acres and has chaparral, grass, and oak trees. It is near a big forest and is home to many animals, some of which are in danger.

People have lived on this land for a long time. Native Americans were there first, and then some people came to raise cattle and sell wood. The land was used for these things for many years.

I found a real farm in the area that is doing this kind of farming. I used this farm as an example to see what kind of help a small farmer might need to make their farm successful and good for the environment.

Culture is important in any discussion. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not the same for everyone. It can be hard to understand. Culture is not one thing. It is not the same everywhere. We should not say that all people from one place are the same. For example, we should not say that all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are polite.

It is better to understand the culture that is important for the discussion. We should know how the culture feels about the issue. We should know how the culture will affect the talk. When we talk to people from another culture, we think about our own culture. We compare them to our own culture. This can be helpful.

To understand a different culture, we can learn about its history. We can learn about its ideas. We can learn about its prejudices. We should not judge another culture. We should accept it as it is. We should work with the culture, not against it. Especially, if we are in a weak position.

In a company, there is a company culture. The company culture is not the same as the national culture. A company culture can be strict or relaxed. A company may like employees to dress a certain way. A company may like employees to communicate in a certain way. A company may like employees to give to charities. Companies in the same country can be very different.

Values are important because they tell us why people behave in certain ways. If people value saving face, they will not make their company or boss look bad. If people value a strong bargain, they will not give in easily. We should know these values before we talk to people from another culture.

It is also good to know the person we are talking to. This can help us talk to them more effectively. We should learn about the person's values and culture. This can help us get what we want.

A famous Bible quote says, “The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This quote is in the Christian Bible and is used by a famous thinker, St. Anselm. We will look at the ideas of St. Anselm and another thinker, Thomas Aquinas. They both believe in the existence of God. We will compare their ideas.

Let us start with the idea of St. Anselm. He thinks that we can find God inside our minds. We all know that God exists, he says. We can see this in our own thoughts. We do not need to look outside for proof. This idea is called faith. Faith means believing in something without proof.

Thomas Aquinas has a different idea. He thinks we can find God by using reason and evidence. We do not need faith to believe in God. He gives five reasons for believing in God: change, cause, an uncertain world, levels of good things, and harmony. He says that these reasons show that God must exist.

We can compare these ideas. St. Anselm’s idea is based on faith. Thomas Aquinas’ idea is based on reason and evidence. We will look at these ideas to see which one is better.

A long time ago, in a place called India, a famous man named Siddhartha was born. He was later known as the Buddha. He gave up his life of wealth and power to find a better way. After many years of study and hard work, he became a wise teacher. His ideas caused many people to start the religion of Buddhism.

Buddhism is now more than 2,500 years old. But it has changed over time. This can be seen in a country called Sri Lanka. The people there celebrate a big festival every year. They cut down a tree to start the festival. The monks and laypeople participate, but the Buddha never taught about this festival. This is just one example of how Buddhism has changed. There are also changes in the rules and ideas of the religion.

These changes can be caused by both friends and enemies. Friends are people who are part of the Buddhist group. Enemies are people who do not like Buddhism. Sometimes friends can change Buddhism in bad ways. Sometimes enemies try to hurt Buddhism.

We need to know some words to understand this discussion. A friend can be a monk or a layperson. A friend is a person who is part of the Buddhist group. An enemy is a person who is not a Buddhist. A bad enemy is a person who wants to hurt Buddhism. A good enemy is a person who does not want to hurt Buddhism but may cause problems anyway.

Now, let's learn about the basic ideas of Buddhism. Buddhists believe in three important things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is a big book of Buddhist texts. It is divided into three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has all the teachings of the Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks and laypeople. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the world and life.

Some important ideas in Buddhism are no soul, suffering, and change. Everything in life is impermanent. If we understand these ideas, we can end the cycle of life and death. We can also end desire, hatred, and confusion. These ideas are like the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. This rivalry was a big problem for both countries. The Mexican-American War was the most important event in this rivalry. The United States won the war and took Texas and the American Southwest from Mexico in 1848.

The United States and Mexico had many disagreements about important things like religion, culture, and money. These disagreements helped create a strong dislike between the two countries. Many other nations with a shared border have similar problems and rivalries.

The United States and Mexico are not alone in having a long rivalry with a neighbor. This is common in countries that share a border. The United States has had long-standing problems with Mexico and Cuba. These countries are close to the United States and have had rivalries with it for a long time.

One of the big issues between the United States and Mexico was about different religions. The United States did not want to be ruled by a king or have the Catholic Church in charge. This was also true in the past with the English and Spanish. 

The United States and Mexico had 17 big disagreements during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these were about border problems. The United States and Mexico used military force to control their borders and stop bandits and outlaws from crossing. 

The rivalry between the United States and Mexico started to get better as Mexico became more dependent on the United States. The United States' goals changed from taking land to helping Mexico's economy. This change helped end the rivalry.

I became very sick fifteen years ago. I had no idea I was going to get sick. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted security and safety. When I was a child, I did not have these things.

A nurse always has a job. People will always get sick. This was what I was told when I grew up. So, I chose to be a nurse instead of being a scientist or a journalist.

But here I am. I am 46 years old and alone. I have no money. I cannot work. I am still sick. I have been on disability for fifteen years. I have no money left.

Every day is hard for me. I need help from my family and friends. I am lucky to have them. When bad things happen, you feel weak. You do not feel strong.

My point is that bad things can happen to anyone. We cannot always prepare for them. We need to help each other. We need to trust each other.

Some people in the United States think we should not depend on the government. But I think we should help each other more. We should help those who need it.

Our ancestors came to America because they had help from their neighbors. They did not come alone. They worked together. We should do the same.

Yes, we should be prepared. I have a disaster kit. I have things to help me if I am hurt. I have food and water. But we should also help each other. We should know our neighbors.

Get to know the people who live near you. This is very important.

Many things happen in nature because of evolution. This is the process of change in living things over many years. People are still trying to understand how and why this change happens. Even in the year nineteen seventeen, biologist D'Arcy Thompson said that scientists have not yet found an easy way to describe how living things are made. Today, scientists are using math to learn about how some animals build their shells.

We are studying how one type of animal builds its shell. This animal is called Prunum. We are using math to help us understand how the shell changes over time. We also studied the animal's shell in different ways. We took pictures of the animal's shell from the inside using X-rays. We used these pictures to make a list of things that describe the shape of the shell. We then put these things into a computer program. This program helps us understand how the shell might change over time.

A shell can be thought of as a tube that grows over time. The shell grows in a spiral way, like a big coil. This coil is made up of many turns, or whorls. The center of the shell is called the columella. The whorls grow at different rates. A line separates each whorl and is called a suture. The biggest whorl is called the body whorl. The rest of the whorls are called the spire. The tip of the spire is called the apex, and the other end is called the base.

We can look at a shell from different angles. There are four main ways to look at a shell: from the top, from the bottom, from the front, and from the back. The most common way to look at a shell is from the front, with the opening facing us.

To count the whorls on a shell, we look at the top of the shell. We find the first line that separates the whorls. We draw a line across the shell at this point. We then count the whorls from this line. We can count them in parts of a whorl.

A shell can be thought of as a path that the animal follows as it grows. The path is made up of many points, or coordinates. We can use math to describe this path. We can also use math to change the way the shell grows. This helps us understand how the animal builds its shell.

In Indonesia, many babies and young children die. Their deaths do not stop. The country is trying to meet goals set by the world to help the poor. But Indonesia is not doing well in helping mothers and children stay healthy. The country is not improving as fast as it should.

Indonesia is making progress in getting health workers at births. Now 72 percent of births have a health worker. But this is not always a good thing. It includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot help if the baby is sick. This is why many mothers die from bleeding during birth.

More children are not getting medical help when they are sick with diarrhea. We do not have good information on how many mothers get good care after they have a baby. But we know that mothers in Indonesia do not get good care.

Not enough mothers have a cesarean section, a type of surgery. Only 4 percent of mothers have this surgery. And it is worse in rural areas. In cities, 7 percent of mothers have a cesarean section, but in rural areas, it is only 2 percent. This is a problem because it means some mothers do not get good care. It also means that some mothers are not treated fairly. The rich have better access to good healthcare.

The problem is that not everyone has access to good healthcare. The poor have a hard time getting medical help. They often have to pay money to get help. And they have to pay a lot if they go to the hospital.

The next step is to fix the lack of healthcare. There are two ways to do this. We can make specific programs to help mothers and children. Or we can make the healthcare system better. The system is like a big machine. If we fix the machine, it will help all parts of the system. 

One way to help mothers and children is to make programs that target one area. These programs can give good results fast. But there are some problems. If we spend a lot of money on one program, we might not have enough for other programs. And if we have many programs, they might not work well together.

Two novels from the Victorian period are not like other novels from this time. They are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These stories have mystery and are a little strange. They help us understand the characters. We see their feelings and reasons for doing things.

In Oliver Twist, strange things happen to the main character. These strange things help us know what is going on inside Oliver's mind. For example, he remembers a shooting in his mind. This shooting makes Oliver very sad and scared. He feels pain and has no control over what is happening to him.

Oliver Twist uses dreams to show us what the main character is feeling. In chapter 28, Oliver remembers the shooting again. This time it feels like a dream. Oliver is very sad and helpless. He cannot change what happened. He is in a lot of pain and is very scared. This shows that Oliver does not have control over his life.

Oliver Twist also shows that Oliver is very sad and defeated. He feels like he cannot do anything. It is like someone, like Fagin, is controlling him and making him feel this way.

Another example of a strange and dreamlike scene is from Wuthering Heights. It says: "The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

This passage describes a long and quiet night. It is like a dream. The writer uses this kind of scene to show how the characters are feeling. It helps us understand their emotions and thoughts.

Both Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights are different from other novels from the Victorian period. They use strange and dreamlike scenes to show us the characters' feelings and thoughts. This makes the characters more interesting and helps us understand them better.

I worked in a program for children after school. I helped students with their homework. My strengths were in English and reading. I worked with a teacher to help a boy named Adrian. He was having a hard time reading. I thought he had a problem. Some letters he could read, but others he could not. It was strange. Adrian spoke perfect English, but I thought he was from a different country. His mother came to the program one day. She did not speak English. We used my bad Spanish to talk. I understood that Adrian did not know the English alphabet. He could read, but he did not know how to read in English.

I tell this story to talk about a problem in schools. Many students have trouble with language. I want to show that it is not always easy to see the problem. Adrian spoke good English, but he still had a problem.

This is a big problem in California and other places. What can we do? One answer is to help students with reading in English. But for students who do not speak much English, it is harder. We need a good plan.

One good part of a plan is dual language programs. This means teaching students in two languages. It is good for students who speak a different language at home. But it is also good for all students. Students in these programs do better in school.

Some people are afraid of this idea. They think it is a waste of money. But it is not true. If we use this idea in all schools, all students will benefit. How can we do this? We do not need all teachers to speak two languages. But we can use helpers who speak two languages.

We can use special helpers in the classroom. They can be tutors or aids. They can help students who need it. This is a good way to help students who have trouble with language.

We can also use other ideas. We can have English as a Second Language (ESL) classes. These classes can help students learn English. We can also use private tutors. These people can help students one-on-one.

The key is to use all of these ideas together. We should not use just one idea. We should use many ideas to help students who have trouble with language.

We learn early in life that there is something bigger than us. Some people go to church to learn about it, while others go to a special place called a temple. Some look inside themselves for answers. We often accept the religions our parents believe in. But some of us do not believe. We may change our ideas about what is important. We look for our own path in life.

My father liked cardinals. We sat on our porch together during the rain. The rain made the plants on the porch wet. My father looked out into the rain. He was thin and his hair was thinning. I felt sad and did not know what to say. I hugged him and sat close to him. We looked out at the rain together.

My father died in December. I was twenty-two years old. He was sick for a long time. The doctors kept him alive, but it was hard for him. I did not want to watch him die. I wanted to remember him when he was alive, not when he was sick. I thought my dad would not want me to watch him die. I stayed in my bed for three days. I was very sad.

I thought about God. I did not know if God was real. If God was real, I thought he was not listening to me. I said no prayers at night. I was angry. I wanted to remember my father, not how he died. I wanted to think about how he lived.

The Gothic Novel is a mix of old and new ideas. Ian Watt says this in his book, "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." People see the Gothic style as a mix of good and bad things. Some say it is not real, while others say it is great. The Gothic style has its roots in old stories and ideas. Horace Walpole's book, "The Castle of Otranto," is the first Gothic Novel. It combines old traditions and new ideas to create a new way of writing.

Walpole uses old-fashioned stories and new ideas to make a new kind of story. He says it is a "Gothic Story." The Gothic style uses ideas from the Middle Ages, like old buildings and old customs. Many people thought the word "gothic" was old-fashioned and not smart. They thought it was not as good as new ideas and ways of writing.

The Gothic style is a mix of old and new ideas. It combines old stories and traditions with new ways of writing. This is why it lasts a long time and is new to people who read it a long time after it was written.

One idea that is important in Gothic stories is the idea of chivalry. Chivalry is a way of training a knight to be brave and honorable. The idea of chivalry is important to Gothic writers because it represents a good knight who is brave and honest. Gothic writers used chivalry to show what was missing in society. They wanted to make the past seem better than the present.

The writer of "The Castle of Otranto" was living in a time when there was a lot of trouble in the world. He was unhappy about the future. He wanted to show that the past was better than the present. He used the idea of chivalry to make the past seem ideal and romantic. He wanted to make people think that the past was better than the present.

In "The Castle of Otranto," there is a character named Frederic. He is a prince who has suffered a lot. He has many qualities of a chivalrous knight. He is brave, kind, and honest. The writer uses Frederic to show what a good knight should be like. Frederic is an example of the Gothic trope of excess, which means being too good to be true.

A supply chain is a flow of things. It includes the steps from getting raw materials to making and delivering products to customers. This idea was first used in 1982 by a business expert named Keith Oliver. He explained how to plan, make, and control the supply chain to meet customers' needs quickly and well.

There are six main parts of a supply chain: making things, getting supplies, storing products, finding a place, moving things, and sharing information. Business managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Making things is the first step. It is the base of the supply chain. It says when, why, where, and how things will be made. Managers need to know what customers want. They can find this out by looking at the market. The market is a good sign of what customers want.

Once managers know what customers want, they decide what products to make and how many. Then they choose where to make the products and which factory will be best. This is based on the customer's needs and satisfaction. Next, managers plan the work and take care of the equipment.

Making things is a very important step. Every detail is very important. If details are not planned well, it can cost a company a lot of time and money. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target. They have a plan for every part of the business. This plan shows how employees should look, how to get products from trucks, and more. Having a plan helps the company work smoothly.

The second key part is getting supplies. This means making strategic decisions to decide what a company can do well. A company may have many groups making the same product. Each group has different equipment and workers. The manager chooses which group is best for each step of making the product. Managers may also decide to work with other companies to make things better.

A manager might choose to work with another company to make things faster and cheaper. This is called velocity. It means making good products quickly and at a low cost.

A sign on a street corner in Burma says Hitler is alive.

Actress Ellen Page, known for her role in the movie Juno, stands alone with a sign. The sign says Burma, now called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia with a bad government. The government came to power in 1962. In 2007, people in Burma protested against their government. The protests were led by Burmese monks. They wore red clothes. The people of Burma started to take notice of the protests. At first, the government allowed the monks to meet peacefully. But then the situation became violent. The military fought the monks. The monks' houses were broken. Foreign reporters were arrested. A Japanese reporter, Kenji Nagai, was killed in 2007 for watching a protest.

This is not new. Governments want to control people. They do not like dissent. This has happened many times in history. Ancient Roman leaders thought they were chosen by gods. Japanese leaders believed they were gods. Some leaders in the United States have talked to a man named Ted Haggard. He leads a group called Stupid People Worldwide.

Many bad things have happened. One example is the protests in Tiananmen Square in 1989. Students and workers protested against their government. The death toll was not clear. Some said 200-300 people died. Others said 2,000-3,000 people died. In Rwanda, Hutu groups killed many people, including those from another group called Tutsis. Hitler's government also killed many people during World War II. They killed anyone who was Jewish.

Duke Ellington is a famous musician. His long career helped make him a great composer. Many of his songs show his good skills as a composer. He often wrote music that let band members show their skills. This was good for the band and made their music sound great. Ellington wrote music that fit the style of each band member. He made music that sounded good together.

Ellington’s piano playing is not very noticeable in some of his music. But he was a great composer. He wrote music that sounded rich and complex. He let band members play freely in his music. He also wrote tightly planned pieces that sounded great with the band.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington’s music. It says he used voice like a musical instrument. This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to make his music sound better. One of his songs, Creole Love Call, is an early example of this. This song is a slow blues song with 12 parts. It has six parts where the voice and the band trade back and forth.

In the first part, the voice sings smoothly. Then it gets rough at the end. In the second part, a trumpet plays a solo. The trumpet makes the basic melody sound better. In the third part, a clarinet plays a solo. The piano plays a simple but nice rhythm. In the fourth part, the whole band plays the first part again. The brass and reed sections trade back and forth. In the fifth part, the reeds start to play the call and response in a high sound. The brass and rhythm sections play a funny stop-and-go rhythm. In the sixth part, the voice and reeds trade back and forth again. This time the voice sounds like a special growl.

Ellington’s use of voice to make his music sound better is one thing he did well. Another example is in the song Hot and Bothered. He wrote tight music and used his ear to make his music sound good. He made a call and response part between a trumpet and a singer. The singer sang in a funny way and the trumpet player played in a special way. This made their music sound rich and good. He also used a trombone player to make the music sound good in another song.

Ellington’s use of voice and his good ear for music made his music sound great. He was a great composer and musician.

This woman always felt something was missing. She was 14 years old when she started feeling this way. It was three years later, at 17, and she still felt the same way. She wanted a person, not a thing. But she was not interested in any boys. Many boys liked her, but none of them interested her. She often asked herself, "What is it that I want?" She thought about this for a long time. She thought maybe it was a boy, but she didn't think so.

This girl was very lucky. Her parents were good people. They never fought with each other. They rarely argued with her. The only time they argued was when she wanted to be independent. Her parents were calm, but she was not. She was fun and loving.

One day, her mother was hurt. She fell off a stool while reaching for a vase. Her daughter heard her scream and ran to help her. "Mom, what's wrong?" she asked. Her mother was in pain and said, "Ouch...sweetie, take me to the hospital." Her daughter helped her mother to the car and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital was a scary place. It smelled bad and there was fear in the air. But she didn't feel scared. She was worried about her mother. She helped her mother get onto a bed and called for the doctors. They took her mother to be looked at. The daughter was left to sit and wait.

This study wanted to see if following a special way of eating, called the Mediterranean Diet, can help prevent heart disease and strokes. The study looked at how well women followed this diet. The Mediterranean Diet is a way of eating that includes many plant foods, nuts, fruits, whole grains, and fish. It also includes some alcohol, but less animal products and fat.

Past studies showed that people who followed this diet were less likely to die from heart disease and other heart problems. This new study wanted to see if it could prevent strokes and deaths from strokes.

The study looked at 74,886 women between 38 and 63 years old who did not have heart disease or diabetes. The women were part of a big study of nurses in 11 states. The women answered questions about what they ate six times between 1984 and 2004. The answers were used to create a score that showed how well they followed the Mediterranean Diet.

The study also looked at other things that might affect the results, like how much the women weighed, if they smoked, and how much they exercised. The study adjusted for these things to get a clearer picture.

The study found that women who followed the Mediterranean Diet more closely were less likely to get heart disease and strokes. They were also less likely to die from these diseases. Women who followed the diet the most were 71% less likely to get heart disease and strokes compared to those who followed it the least.

In 2007, the United States had a very bad financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, and the value of homes fell. Some very big companies failed. This situation is still bad today. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it.

The financial crisis was caused by bad decisions made by people in government. They wanted banks and companies to give loans to people who could not pay them back. This was done in a country with weak financial systems. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two big companies, were asked to make these bad loans into something called CDOs.

When people could not pay their loans, banks lost money. They sold the bad loans to other companies and to the rest of the economy. This caused big problems.

The roots of the financial crisis started in 1999. President Clinton wanted to be re-elected. He wanted to be popular, so he loosened rules about lending. This helped create the problem of bad loans seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said at that time, “Fannie Mae is giving more loans to people who cannot pay them back.” He said this could cause big problems in the future.

Many things happened together to make the economy very bad. New types of mortgages made things worse. These were mortgages that could change their interest rates, and they were very complicated. This made people and banks take too many risks.

The value of homes fell, and many people could not pay their mortgages. The big banks that had these bad loans were in big trouble. In 2007, these banks had $4.1 trillion in bad debts. This was 30% of the total value of the United States.

Four big banks, Bear Sterns, Merrill Lynch, Lehman Brothers, and Goldman Sachs, lost a lot of money. They were forced to change what they did. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in bad loans and were taken over by the government.

Exposition is a part of writing that can be tricky. It is the part where you tell your readers about events and things that happened before the main story starts. But too much exposition can be boring. It is like a long, slow walk on a quiet street. You might start to feel sleepy.

The problem with exposition is that it is easy to use too much. You might think, "I want to tell you everything about this character." But the reader does not need to know everything. They just need to know what is important.

Imagine you are reading a story and you are told that the heroine met her husband at a party, got married in a big ceremony, and then he was murdered in front of her. That would take a lot of time. The writer would have to tell you a lot of details. But it would be better to show you this part of the story instead of just telling you. For example, you could see how the heroine and her husband talk to each other. You could see how much they love each other. This way, you would care about what happens to him when he dies.

As a writer, you have to give your readers the right amount of information. You do not want to give them too much or too little. If you give them too much, they might get bored. If you give them too little, they might not understand what is happening.

It is like cooking a meal. You have to put the right amount of salt and pepper in the food so it tastes good. If you put too much salt, it is too salty. If you put too little salt, it is not tasty.

So, remember, as a writer, you need to be careful with exposition. Give your readers just the right amount of information so they can enjoy your story.

I watched two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife. The man's name is Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture and he looked very bad. They spent two minutes on this story. The wife was hurt badly and the man was arrested. I think they spent the right amount of time on this story.

The next story was about a boy named Travis Buyers, 18, who was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was very badly hurt but no one was arrested yet. The police were investigating. This story was short. I think it was short because the boy is black and lives in a black neighborhood. I noticed that when a white person is hurt or missing, the news talks about it a lot. But when a minority person is hurt or missing, it is not talked about as much.

The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. The police think a small bullet from a rifle hit the helicopter. They are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for information about who did it.

The next story was about the weather. They said it would be hot and stormy on Saturday afternoon. The temperature would be high.

The next story was about a robbery at a Clime Road store. The police said a tall, black man with a black hoodie robbed the store. They spent a lot of time talking about how black the man was. This seemed strange.

The next story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He is a convicted drug dealer from Texas. He was sent to prison for 300 months. They also said he is Hispanic. I don't think this was important to the story.

There is a special feeling between brothers. It is strong and hard to break. This feeling has many parts: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers know each other better than anyone else. They can see themselves in their brother. This bond is clear when things get very bad. When brothers see the good or bad things in their bond, they have to deal with the results. When one brother looks at another and sees himself, he sees who he really is. He sees his true character in his actions and what happens because of them.

In the story "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this idea. They go on a journey through a beautiful place. They are very different. One brother is very sick and can't do many things. The healthy brother is very disappointed. He wanted a brother to play with and learn from. He wanted someone to be with him in exciting activities. But the sick brother can't do those things. The healthy brother feels angry and sad. He even thought about hurting his brother. But when his brother smiles, he feels a little better. This shows that he loves his brother.

The story is about a boy named Doodle. He is sick and can't play like other children. His brother wants to teach him things, but Doodle can't do them. The brother feels sad and angry because his brother can't be what he wants him to be. But when Doodle smiles, his brother feels a little better.

The story shows how brothers feel about each other. They can love and be angry at the same time. They can see themselves in their brother and learn about themselves. The story is about the special bond between brothers.

The brain is a very important and complicated system. It helps us think and remember.  Long ago, people thought of the brain like a slate, a piece of paper, and a book. Later, they thought of it like a computer. But these pictures are not very good. They can lead to mistakes.

The brain works like a machine. It takes in information from our senses. Our senses feel, see, and hear things. They turn these things into signals that the brain can understand. The brain then changes these signals many times. This is called processing. There are two kinds of processing: one goes from simple to complex, and the other uses the brain's decisions to help us recognize things faster.

For example, when you see a picture of a box, the brain puts together small pieces of information like color and shape. Then it decides that you are seeing a box. The brain also uses what it already knows to help you decide that it's a box and not a hole. It's like your brain is helping your brain.

The brain has a filter that decides which signals are important. It sends the important signals to the right parts of the brain. For example, you might hear many different sounds, but you only pay attention to the sound of your name. The brain has many steps of processing, and it repeats this filtering many times.

The brain needs to store information to process it. There are three kinds of memory: short-term, working, and long-term. Short-term memory is like a computer screen. It keeps information for a short time, like 20 seconds. Working memory is like a computer program that stores information for a short time. Long-term memory is like a computer that stores information forever.

There are many ways to understand how the brain stores information. Some scientists study how people remember things. Others study computers. Still, others study how the brain works. One idea is that the brain has a network of ideas. Each idea is connected to other ideas like it. For example, the idea of a chair is connected to the idea of a table, which is connected to the idea of wood.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the dangers of technology and capitalism in his novel Brave New World. He creates a society where people value community over individual freedom. They are taught from birth to be happy and not think too much. The citizens are like pawns in a game, controlled by the World Controller. Huxley is worried about the future and the way people are being treated.

In Brave New World, people are not thinking for themselves. They are controlled by the people in charge. This is like the idea of false consciousness in Marxism. The common people do not know about the relationship between different groups in society. They are too busy thinking about themselves. This is because the people in charge control what they think and do. The lower classes are not aware of this. They are happy to buy and consume, and do not think about the system they live in. The people in charge are also not doing anything to change things. They just accept their position.

In Brave New World, people do not have deep relationships. They do not have strong feelings like love or hate. They just talk about physical things, like how someone looks. This is because they are not allowed to have deep feelings. The people in the different social classes are happy with their place in society. This shows how capitalism affects people's lives. They do not think about anything else, and just follow the rules.

Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism take away people's free will and individuality. People are not allowed to be different or think for themselves. They just do what they are told. This is what Huxley is trying to show in his novel.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years. Getting around campus can be hard. In my first year, I lived in East Halls, a place far from the center of campus. My home in Stuart Hall was very far from my classes in Willard building. It took 25 minutes to walk from my home to class, especially on bad days. I met an older student and asked about the old East Halls dorms. He told me they were once far from the rest of the school. Now, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus grows, getting around becomes harder. The best way to solve this problem is with bicycles. But it is not just about the bike. Students need to ride them, and the campus must be made for cyclists.

I talked to a friend who started riding again after a few years. He said, "Bikes are great. It is the best way to get around." Bicycling is good for your body and the most efficient way to travel. You can go 30 miles or more with a bowl of oatmeal and some exercise. I live off campus, far from the center of campus. I bought a bike this year and it was a smart decision. I have class in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding my bike takes only 5 minutes. However, Pollock Road is not a safe road to ride on. Walking is also good, but I am too busy to walk. If I didn't have a bike, I would have to walk to class, which would take 30-40 minutes every day. That is two and a half hours every week. I do not have that much time.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.  Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean.  Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness.  Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxious the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again.  The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid.  A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt.   Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….
